In addition to seasonal effects, the Martian atmosphere exhibits a strong thermal tide excited by direct solar heating of the atmosphere on the day side and strong infrared cooling on the night side. Heating causes an inflation of the atmosphere with a simultaneous drop in the atmospheric column depth and surface pressure. In Gale Crater, the thermal tide produces a diurnal variation of column mass of about ±5%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
