The heliospheric impact includes both short-term influences by solar transients and the long-term solar cycle evolution (Sect. 4). On short time scales, the GCR flux can be altered temporarily in the form of Forbush decreases (FDs) by transient heliospheric magnetic structures such as interplanetary coronal mass ejections and stream interaction regions. FDs have been observed since decades at Earth by ground neutron monitors; now RAD has also provided a new dataset of the FDs observed at Mars since 2012 August (Guo et al. 2018b; Papaioannou et al. 2019). These FDs have been analyzed in various works for identifying the shock, CME and SIR arrival at Mars and for studying the propagation and evolution of such solar transients and their space weather effect at Mars in synergy with in situ plasma and magnetic field measurements or even when such measurements are missing (Witasse et al. 2017; Winslow et al. 2018; Guo et al. 2018a; Wang et al. 2018; Dumbović et al. 2019; Freiherr von Forstner et al. 2018, 2019, 2020). Over the time period from August 2012 until June 2020, the RAD GCR dose rate increased by ∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
